08.Unit Standards

Primary Standards

Primary unit standards are precise definitions of physical variables. Some examples of standards in everyday use are:

  • United States Customary Units (USCS or USC)
  • Imperial Units
  • English Units
  • English Engineering Units
  • International System of Units (SI)

The SI system (the SI comes from the French Systme International (d'units)) is the most prevalent by far. Many of the other unit systems listed above are based in some way or form upon units defined in the SI system. As such, we'll focus our attention on the SI units because, with this system's knowledge, almost all the other systems may be understood. There are seven different primary standards in the SI system. The seven different SI primary standards are:

  • Time - second ($s$)
  • Mass - kilogram ($kg$)
  • Amount of substance - mole ($mol$)
  • Luminous intensity - candela ($cd$)
  • Temperature - Kelvin ($K$)
  • Current - ampere ($A$)
  • Length - meter ($m$)

With these seven units, and only these seven units, all other units that may be needed can be defined. If these seven units can be precisely defined, there is no worry of other special definitions. All that is needed are the seven primary standards, and everything else falls into place. As of May 20th, 2019, the primary standards for the SI system were updated. Now there is no need to worry about going out and buying a new meter stick. The SI system was updated so that the units stayed the same for the everyday user. Before 2019, the last major change occurred in 1960. The following changes were made.

  • 4 of the 7 were redefined; $kg$, $A$, $K$, and $mol$
  • 2 were corrected; $m$, and $cd$

Time

The second is defined as $$ 1s \equiv \frac{9,192,631,770}{\Delta \nu_{Cs}} $$

where $ \Delta \nu_{Cs} $ is the frequency of the radiation corresponding to the transition between two hyperfine levels of the ground state of cesium-133 atom. Now you may be asking, why in the world would you define the second like this?! Quite often, time is thought of in terms of the rotation of the Earth (remember rotation is around its central axis, revolution is around the Sun). The common thought is that the time it takes for the Earth to rotate once (i.e., one day) is 24 hours, and from there, the time of a second may be found (the Earth's rotation time divided by $24 \times 60 \times 60$ or $86400$). So a second could be defined as $ 1 / 86400th$ of one Earth's rotation. The only problem is that the Earth's rotation is not constant (see here). The Earth's rotation is slowing down, so using the Earth's rotation definition of a second, a second today would be faster than a second tomorrow or 1000 years from now. Another common thought is the second may be determined by the revolution of the Earth around the Sun. A second by this definition would then be $ 1 / 31536000 $ ($ 365 \times 24 \times 60 \times 60 $) of the time it takes to revolve around the Sun. However, this definition has a similar issue to the rotation definition. The Earth's revolution around the Sun is slowing down. There's also the issue with leap years. Is the second shorter on a leap year? With the SI system's definition of the second, there is no issue of the second changing because the definition is based upon a universal constant, the radiation frequency of a particular isotope. As far as we humans know, the radiation frequency of the cesium-133 atom is a universal constant. It is the same today as 1000 years ago and will be the same in another 1000 years. This consistency is why the definition is so great. With a properly equipped lab, anyone anywhere can determine what a second is precisely. Shown below in Figure 1 is the FOCS 1, a continuous cold cesium atomic clock in Switzerland.

Figure 1: The FOCS 1

The FOCS 1 started in 2004 and has an uncertainty of $1s$ in 30 million years ($9.46728\times10^{14}s$).

Mass

The primary standard for mass is one of the recent updates to the SI system. The old definition should first be understood to understand the motivation of providing a new definition. The old definition is

  1. The kilogram is the mass of a platinum-iridium cylinder called "International Prototype Kilogram" (IPK), sometimes called Le Grand K, kept at the International Bureau of Weights and Measurements in France.

Shown below in Figure 2 is a picture of the IPK.

Figure 2: The International Prototype Kilogram

At it's simplest, the IPK is just a hunk of metal. Granted, it's a special hunk of metal in that it has been precisely machined to specific dimensions and then highly polished. It's kept under lock and key in a vault in France. It is essential to emphasize that the IPK is not $1kg$, but what we call $1kg$ is the same mass as the IPK. The IPK defines what the kilogram is not the other way around.

For this reason, if the IPK were modified in any way (mass added to it, mass removed from it), the kilogram would no longer be what we know it to be. The kilogram would be whatever the mass of the IPK is. Therefore, the IPK is kept in a vault under lock and key. There are problems with this definition, as you might imagine. What happens if the IPK is damaged? France is far away. What if I need access to the IPK? Mass drift has been seen in the comparison of the IPK to sister copies. The mass drift is shown in Figure 3 below.

Figure 3: IPK vs Sister Copies

Sister copies are copies made of the IPK to very close tolerance. They are made to be precisely like the IPK. However, looking at the plot in Figure 3, it may be seen that the mass of the IPK and sister copies are changing over time. The y-axis shows the difference between the masses of the IPK and each sister copy (each line/series on the plot is for a different sister copy). One of the few options may be happening.

  • All sister copies gained mass
  • The IPK is losing mass
  • A combination of both

For this reason, a new definition is being used. The new definition is

$$ 1kg \equiv \frac{\left( 299,792,458 \right)^2}{\left( 6.62607015 \times 10^{-34} \right)\left( 9,192,631,770 \right)} \frac{h \Delta \nu_{Cs}}{c^2} $$

where

  • $h$ is the Planck constant
  • $ \Delta \nu_{Cs} $ is as defined previously
  • $ c $ is the speed of light in a vacuum

Once again, you might ask, why in the world would you define the kilogram like this?! The same as in the case of the second still applies. All of these quantities ($h$, $\Delta \nu_{Cs}$, and $c$) are universal constants. They are not going to change. With a properly equipped lab, anyone anywhere may determine what a kilogram is. There is also no risk of losing or damaging something like the IPK. Universal constants can't be lost or damaged.

Amount Of Substance

The old definition is

  1. The mole is the amount of substance of a system containing as many elementary entities as atoms in $ 0.012 kg$ of carbon-12.

Remember, carbon-12 is a specific isotope of the carbon atom. Shown below in Figure 4 is the notation for the carbon-12 isotopes.

Figure 4: Carbon-12 Isotope

The issue with this definition is that it can be difficult to count individual atoms. For this reason, the definition has been revised. The new definition is

$$ 1 mol \equiv \frac{6.02214076 \times 10^{23}}{N_A} $$

where $ N_A$ is the Avogadro constant. The Avogadro constant is name after the Italian scientist Amedeo Avogadro who lived from 1776 to 1856. Figure 5 is a portrait of Avogadro.

Figure 5: Amedeo Avogadro

Once again, this new definition provides a definition that is in terms of universal constants. While the old definition was in terms of a universal constant, it was somewhat difficult to achieve. This new definition provides both an adequate definition and ease of use.

Luminous Intensity

The old definition is

  1. The luminous intensity, in a given direction, of a source that emits monochromatic radiation of frequency $ 540 \times 10^2 Hz$ and of which the radiant intensity in that direction is $ \frac{1}{683} \frac{W}{sr} $.

$sr$ stands for steradian and is a solid angle. A steradian is to a sphere as a radian is to a circle. You can think of a steradian "cutting out" a circle with an area of $r^2$. A diagram of a steradian is shown below in Figure 6.

Figure 6: Steradian

The new definition is

$$ 1 cd \equiv \frac{K_{cd} h c \Delta \nu_{Cs}}{\left( 683 \right)\left( 6.62607015 \times 10^{-34} \right)\left( 299,792,458 \right)\left( 9,192,631,770 \right)} $$

where $K_{cd}$ is the luminous efficacy of monochromatic radiation of frequency $540 \times 10^2 Hz$ and all the other constants are as previously described. Luminous efficacy is a measure of well a light source produces light. The $540 \times 10^2 Hz$ frequency is a greenish light.

Temperature

The old definition is

  1. The Kelvin is $ 1 / 273.16 $ of the triple point of water.

Remember, the triple point of water is where all three phases of water exist simultaneously. A phase diagram of water with its triple point location is shown below in Figure 7.

Figure 7: Water Phase Diagram with Triple Point Location

The new definition is

$$ 1 K \equiv \frac{1.380649 \times 10^{-23}}{\left( 6.62607015 \times 10^{-34} \right)\left( 9,192,631,770 \right)} \frac{h \Delta \nu_{Cs}}{k} $$

where $k$ is the Boltzman constant and all other constants are as previously defined.

Current

The old definition is

  1. The ampere is the constant current that occurs in two straight parallel conductors of infinite length, and negligible circular sections placed $1$ meter apart in a vacuum producing a force equal to $2 \times 10^{-7} N/m$.

Now, this may seem like a complicated definition for something like the ampere, which is typically thought of as being the number of electrons that flow through a given point in one second. But if the definition is taken apart piece by piece, it can fully be understood. Consider the diagram shown below in Figure 8.

Figure 8: Old Ampere Definition

Figure 8 shows two conducting rods (the gray ones) that are spaced one meter apart. The red arrows show the flow of electricity through each conductor. Whenever electricity is passed through a conductor, a magnetic field is created around the conductor normal to the electricity flow. This magnetic field is how electromagnets that you made as a kid work. The coils of the wire in the electromagnet magnify the magnetic effect, but there is a magnetic field even in a single strand of wire. The blue arrows show the force of attraction between the two conductors. Once the force of attraction between the two conducting rods reaches a force of $2 \times 10^{-7} N$ (the blue arrows), the current flow is said to be one ampere. The new definition is

$$ 1 A \equiv \frac{e \Delta \nu_{Cs}}{\left( 1.602176634 \times 10^{-19} \right)\left( 9,192,631,770 \right)} $$

where $e$ is the elementary charge and $\Delta \nu_{Cs}$ is as previously defined. The elementary charge is the electric charge carried by one proton.

Length

The meter has an interesting definition history. At one time it was

  1. One ten-millionth of the distance between the north pole and the equator at Paris's longitude.

The problem with this definition is that we now know that the north pole and Paris locations are not constant. The north pole location moves due to a phenomenon known as polar drift. The location of Paris changes due to plate tectonics. From 1889 to 1960, a prototype meter made of platinum and iridium was used as the meter. Figure 9, shown below, shows these prototype meters.

Figure 9: Platinum and iridium prototype meter stick

The old definition is

  1. The meter is the length of the path traveled by light in a vacuum during a duration of $1/299,792,458$ of a second.

The new definition of the meter refines this previous definition even further. The new definition is

$$ 1 m \equiv \frac{9,192,631,770}{299,792,458} \frac{c}{\Delta \nu_{Cs}} $$

Terminology of Standards

There are a couple of different terms that you'll come across when discussing different types of standards. The first is a fixed standard. A fixed standard is one that cannot be reproduced in a lab. Before the 2019 SI system revision, there was only one fixed standard in the SI system, the mass standard. It was fixed because it was set by a physical device (IPK) that could not be reproduced in a lab. Sure, copies could be made of the IPK, but without access to the IPK, there would be no way of knowing what a kilogram was. The second term that is common is a reproducible standard. A reproducible standard is one that may be reproduced in a properly equipped lab. With the 2019 SI system revision, all the SI system standards are reproducible standards. With the right know-how and a properly equipped lab, all seven SI system standards may be obtained. Reproducible standards are a great achievement but quite often are not practical. You don't want to have to measure the speed of light in a vacuum every time you need to measure the length of something. In these cases is where secondary standards come in handy. Secondary standards are standards that have been compared to a primary standard at some point in time. The term also applies to a standard that has been compared to a secondary standard. If there is a directly traceable connection to a primary standard and the standard, the standard is a secondary standard. One example of a secondary standard is a standard mass set, as shown below in Figure 10.

Figure 10: Standard Mass Set

Standard mass sets are ones that, in some way, have been compared to the mass definition previously discussed. The more expensive sets come with a certificate stating their lineage to the primary standard and are handled with gloves to prevent oils from your hands throwing off the masses. Another example of a secondary standard are gage blocks. Some gage blocks are shown below in Figure 11.

Figure 11: Gage Blocks

Gage blocks are usually blocks of steel that have been precisely machined and then highly polished to very accurate thicknesses. The different blocks are then placed together to create the desired length to be measured. Figure 10 depicts $10mm$, $20mm$, and $50mm$ blocks to create an overall length of $80mm$. The reason for the use of gloves with gage blocks is twofold. First, it prevents the oils from your hands throwing off the blocks' accuracy, and second, the moisture introduced from your hands could cause the blocks to start rusting.
